Abstract

The key focus of this report is to build a prediction model from the dataset of a Steinmetz et al. (2019) study; for feedback type of mice who are visually stimulated, and rewarded/punished based on their response, specifically the focus of neurological activity 4 seconds post feedback type. Brain area activity, session homogeneity and spices of neurons play a key role in allowing predictions to be built, based on the response of a mouse to a stimuli selection, that encompasses visual, sensory, and choice making neurons. Though utilization of STA141A lectures and discussion notes the creating of this report was possible

Introduction

The sourse of my data is provided though the STA141A course at UCD, and is a collection of 1-18 sessions (with 100 trials removed from Sessions 1 and 18) of the Steinmetz et al. (2019) study that is described in detail in the Background section of this report.

My question for this report is:

What is an optimal amount and type of brain areas usage to receive positive feedback, and are the outcomes impacted by the gender of mice?

Are vision, action and choice neurons correlated to the gender of mice, and is it a good functional estimate to build a prediction model on?

My setup is to alienate factors and pin them against feedback type in order to determine the most powerful ones that may allow me to form a powerful prediction model. I will then determine an interaction effect between factors that seem inportant to me and demonstrate their impact though visual figures. To train and test the prediction model I am interested in a 80% split of the data, and a clustering method, perhaps a K-means or a KNN methods as those are the most fitting for the size and binomial (1 positive feedback; -1 negative feedback) nature of this dataset.

Key factors I looked into are:

  • Gender

  • Brain Area Number for Positive Feedback

  • Contributing Brain Areas to Positive Feedback

  • Left and Right stimuli v.s. Zero and Same stimuli

  • Session Number

Background

The prime method of this report is to create a prediction model, that is capable of predicting feedback type of a trial based on spikes(neurological activity) and stimuli (left, right, same, or none) of the mice.

The data is derived from Steinmetz et al. (2019), where Neuropixels probes were utilized to gather information from 30,000 neurons across 42 brain areas. 10 mice over 39 sessions were used for this study, where they were visually stimulated, of contrasting levels, that are represented by {0, 0.25, 0.50, 1.0}. There are four of the following outcomes that may happen during the study resulting to feed back levels of 1 (rewarded some water) and -1 (mistake and a punishment):

  1. Left is brighter than right: 1 when a wheel is turned to the right, and -1 otherwise
  2. Right is brighter than left: 1 when a wheel is turned to the left, and -1 otherwise
  3. Both sides are equal levels, but not 0: left or right are randomly chosen to be the correct answer
  4. Both sides are equal and are 0: 1 is given if the wheel is not turned either way (held still for 1.5s), -1 otherwise

Neurological activity of mice is constructed through three types of neurons: visual, perceptual, and decision making. Such as for example Visual kernel neurons are located in the lateral and primary visual areas cortex of the brain, abbreviated as: VISI, VISp and VISpl.

Sensory neurons are located in the sematorensoty area part of the cortex and are abbreviated such as: SSp and SSs.

Choice neurons are the rarest observed, and they are found in the frontal cortex, such as abbreviated: MOs, PL andMOp. There neurons are also found in

The first table demonstrates a general layout of the dataset, that is four mice: Cori, Forssmann, Hench, and Laderberg. Their success rate (positive feedback after rotating the wheel in the correct direction or not rotating it at all) is linked to the amount of brain areas that the mice have used, as well as the number of trials and neurons that it took them.

Feedback type is based of the positive retrieval of a reward in form of water (1) and a negative effect, that ( not described explicitly may be no water given to mouse).

There are as mentioned four stimuli conditions, and I will exemplify them (they range 0-1 in 0.25 increments):

  • Left: 0.25 and Right: 1 - this is a Right stimuli and will require a mouse to turn the wheel left

  • Left : 0.75 and Right: 0.00 - this is a Left stimuli and will require a mouse to turn the wheel right

  • Left: 0.00 and Right: 0.00 - this is a Zero stimuli and will require a mouse to keep the wheel straight for 1.5 seconds.

  • Left: 0.50 and Right: 0.50 - this is a Same stimuli and will require a mouse to chose one Left or Right direction to turn the wheel to, and the correct decision will be chosen by the people running the experiment (random 50% chance)

In the first “Number of Neurons and Success Rate” graph I explore the relationship between the neurological activity of the mice, the success rate of their responses, as well as the amount of brain areas connected to each of the observations.

The main goal of this task is to determine how many brain areas I want to observe for my final prediction model, since this would give me an optimal amount of intersection in neuron activity. The average number of brain areas is shown to be 9.5, and the median at 10, for the next step I wan tot determine the most significant number of brain areas, especially when the mice are gendered, since the test data will come from female mice (subset from Sessions 1 and 18)

Most observations are clumped below the 1200 number of neurons, yet do demonstrate a wide spread between the success rates. An interesting observation I kept seeing is the importance of 6 brain areas, that produce consistent success levels above 0.72, that is a good indicator for my predictive model.

Due to my interest in gendering the mice, I included these two graphs, one for female mice, and another for male mice, and the connection of the amount of brain ares they utilized, in connection to feedback type. And once again 6 brains demonstrates a discrepancy between the quotas of the plots. Now I will demonstrate how I chose the 6 brain areas that I will use as benchmark for my prediction model. Since this is an extremely surface comparison, I wanted to look at a third factor that might contribute to the final prediction model.

Data Integration

I used a behavioral approach to view the i,pact of 6 brain areas that I have mentioned in my data exploration step. As well as the gender difference of the mice.

A very interesting observation that I discovered is the visible difference in brain activities of mice with an obvious stimuli (right or left) to that of zero stimulus or same side (aka equal) stimulus. A comment I would like to make, is that for equal stimulus category researchers randomized their decision of whick side was the correct one, thus punishing mice that chose the opposite side, which I think may have created a great confusion for mice, since they work great on repetitive system learning.

Both genders of mice demonstrate an equated brain area activity density for both feedback types when the stimuli are both zero. Yet the observation of 15 brain areas in male mice demonstrates a significant difference (bigger in the positive feedback category), as that of female mice, who demonstrate insignificant difference in the two feedback types.

For the same, but non-zero stimuli, the observations are similar to those zero stimuli in their overall shape, especially for female mice. The male mice on the other hand show a significant upsurge in negative feedback responses specifically in 6, 12, and 13 brain area usage. Female mice notably demonstrate a growth in negative feedback in 12 brain areas usage.

For distinct stimuli both female and male mice represent an increase in positive feedback density, demontrating that a flushed out stimulus allows mice to make decisions and learn the correct decision of wheel rotation, compared to the zero and equal stimuli that demonstrate equal density.

Now, I’m interested in investigating closer sessions 2,16, and 17 as those are female mice sessions (just like the test data that will be using my prediction model on) that use 6 brain areas, specifically the positive feedback, as it was shown to have more responsive correlation to neurological functions of mice.

The brain area outputs session have been chosen based on the graph shown in Part1 and trial number was randomized through the Google random number generator.

This particular table demonstrates Session 2, Trial 4 that uses 5 brain areas and demonstrates an average success level of 63%, and is for a Female mouse. Just to get a general idea of what exactly these brain ares represent, I looked at the original publication:

CA1 is located in the hippocampal memory system and plays a part in episodic memory retrieval

POST is a memory allocated neuron as well

root is a transmitter of sensory information towards the central nervous system (shows up in every trial)

VISI is visual neuron that does not contain choice selection

VISpm is another visual kernel counterpart

Interesting observation that I found is that as the trials go on, Visual kernels slowly decrease, which does make sense as the mouse gets increasingly tired over time.

Data Integration

## Loading required package: lattice

For the data integration model I decided to use the K-Nearest Neighbors with a 3 fold cross-validation and setting the k-number to 10 , since it utilizes both classification and regression and showed to be an incredible method in Assignment 4.

This method relies on selecting a number (k) of nearest neighbors, then finding the Euclidean distance between the observations and KKN, and figuring out an optimal amount of KNN to apply for the model to give us the closest results possible. I used specifically the Elbow method that reiterated through the Nearest Neighbors in order to pin point the best amount.

I am limited widely due to my lack of skill and experience using R (my first course actually coding) to create the perfect data frame of each session, its averaged spikes to brain areas (ones I depicted above) and gender of the mice to create the perfect model.

Instead, My process of model selection consisted of using brain areas as a big factor, as it demonstrated that the amount of ares used can optimize the positive feedback of a mouse and decrease it trial through trial exhaustion. Gender was a factor I implemented into the data frame myself, as I have seen the divide between the neurological function between the male and female mice. Through a little bit of testing I also implemented stimuli sides, primarily due to the demonstration of gendered plots of four cases of stimuli all showing that feedback type relies on the initial stimuli. I used 80% of my data towards training and 10% towards testing (mainly to see demonstrate that my pre-official test data model is functional at all).

This is a confusion matrix, that depicts Predicted and Observed values in a True False manner with criteria such as True Negative, True Positive, False Positive and False Negative, thus putting a rather tough prediction into a nicely understandable table.

Precision is the proportion of correctly predicted values by this model out of all positively predicted instances, and it is depicted to be 72.65%.

Recall a.k.a Sensitivity is the ratio of positively predicted instances out of all instances (identification of all positive instances) and it is 92.48%.

The F1-score is a mix of Precision and Recall and it is 82.57%

Conclussion

To conclude this report I would like to say that my model did in fact better than I anticipated, as I have very low skill level and therefore confidence. My choice of modeling and clustering the data was through the KNN approach, which offered me much insight and wiggle room to play around with various fold amounts, factors for the model, and methods. A real world application of this study, and specifically the predictive model would allow humans to understand the hierarchy of visual, senstory, and choice neurons, and the intersectionality of them all. In the age of mass media and people being chronically-online, that are visual stimuli that urge us to make choices by controlling the screen, like the mice controlling the wheel, we can determine what parts of our brains are the most responsive, and find a way to predict a response/reaction out of people consuming the visual stimulus. Such can be useful for the entertainment industry, marketing teams, and even in education settings. My findings demonstrate that the intersection of gender and neurological activity yields different responses in mice, specifically due to the fact that male mice perform better with no clear choice given, whereas female mice do a better job at explicit solutions, as well as 6 brain area usage being the most optimal for a correct response. I also outlines CA1, LD, root and SSp to be the most used and predictive brain areas among the 4 mice tried. My prediction model demonstrated that the interaction effect between gender, brain areas amount, brain-spikes, and visual contract stimuli.

An area I can see myself improving is through the data mining, as I spent days and days trying to subset the data of my dream (one with specific brain areas) but I just couldn’t figure out how to go about it, therefore had to go into the modeling phase with the amount of data I was able to extract. This I am confident in, that it would improve my predictive perfomance significantly, and be more informative. Room to grow:)

forssmann.m.left = forssmann.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left) > as.numeric(contrast_right))
forssmann.m.right = forssmann.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_right) > as.numeric(contrast_left))
forssmann.m.two = forssmann.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left)==as.numeric(contrast_right))
forssmann.m.same = forssmann.m.two %>% filter(contrast_right != 0)
forssmann.m.none = forssmann.m.two %>% filter(contrast_left == 0)


hench.m.left = hench.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left) > as.numeric(contrast_right))
hench.m.right = hench.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_right) > as.numeric(contrast_left))
hench.m.two = hench.m %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left)==as.numeric(contrast_right))
hench.m.same = hench.m.two %>% filter(contrast_right != 0)
hench.m.none = hench.m.two %>% filter(contrast_left == 0)


lederberg.f.left = lederberg.f %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left) > as.numeric(contrast_right))
lederberg.f.right = lederberg.f %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_right) > as.numeric(contrast_left))
lederberg.f.two = lederberg.f %>% filter(as.numeric(contrast_left)==as.numeric(contrast_right))
lederberg.f.same = lederberg.f.two %>% filter(contrast_right != 0)
lederberg.f.none = lederberg.f.two %>% filter(contrast_left == 0)


fem = rbind(cori.f,lederberg.f)
fem.left = rbind(cori.f.left, lederberg.f.left)
fem.right = rbind(cori.f.right, lederberg.f.right)
fem.same = rbind(cori.f.same, lederberg.f.same)
fem.none = rbind(cori.f.none, lederberg.f.none)


male = rbind(forssmann.m, hench.m)
male.left = rbind(forssmann.m.left,hench.m.left)
male.right = rbind(forssmann.m.right,hench.m.right)
male.same = rbind(forssmann.m.same,hench.m.same)
male.none = rbind(forssmann.m.none,hench.m.none)

fem.correct = fem %>% filter(feedback_type == 1)
fem.incorrect = fem %>% filter(feedback_type != 1)
male.correct = male %>% filter(feedback_type == 1)
male.incorrect = male %>% filter(feedback_type != 1)

  summarize(mean= mean(spikes))
average_spike_area<-function(i.t,this_session){
  spk.trial = this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area= this_session$brain_area
  spk.count=apply(spk.trial,1,sum)
  spk.average.tapply=tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
  return(spk.average.tapply)
  }
average_spike_area(1,this_session = session[[i.s]])

n.trial=length(session[[i.s]]$feedback_type)
n.area=length(unique(session[[i.s]]$brain_area ))
 


trial.summary =matrix(nrow=n.trial,ncol= n.area+1+2+1)
for(i.t in 1:n.trial){
  trial.summary[i.t,]=c(average_spike_area(i.t,this_session = session[[i.s]]),
                          session[[i.s]]$feedback_type[i.t],
                        session[[i.s]]$contrast_left[i.t],
                        session[[i.s]]$contrast_right[i.s],
                        i.t)
}

colnames(trial.summary)=c(names(average_spike_area(i.t,this_session = session[[i.s]])), 'feedback', 'left contr.','right contr.','id' )

# Turning it into a data frame
trial.summary <- as_tibble(trial.summary)

  lines(y=trial.summary[[i]],x=trial.summary$id,col=area.col[i],lty=2,lwd=1)
  lines(smooth.spline(trial.summary$id, trial.summary[[i]]),col=area.col[i],lwd=3)
  }
legend("topright", 
  legend = colnames(trial.summary)[1:n.area], 
  col = area.col, 
  lty = 1, 
  cex = 0.8

library("caret")

set.seed(555)

trainit = createDataPartition(df$feedback_type, p = 0.80, list = FALSE)
train <- df[trainit,]
test1 <- df[-trainit,]



trainControl = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3)
metric = "Accuracy"

set.seed(111)
my.knn = train(feedback_type ~ brain_area + gender + as.numeric(spks) + contrast_right+ contrast_left, data =train, method = "knn", 
               metric = metric,
               trControl = trainControl
               )

knn.k1 = my.knn$bestTune

print(my.knn)

plot(my.knn)

set.seed(767)
pred = predict(my.knn, newdata = test1)
conf = confusionMatrix(pred,test1$feedback_type)
print(conf)
